{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689925/1958041601/0508.xml":{"full_text":"TMB KEY WEST CITI2EN Wedneodoy, April 14, 1918\nPage 6\nThe Key West Citizen\nPubliihM Sunday Morning and Every Week Dey Afternoon,\nExeept Saturday\nM/kDuiv n ARTMAN Udi tor A Publisher\nS^nGARET roWUM* Citf .Kdltee\nFt at ri IB t Art t Art 1\u00bbl n t Ma nager\nBlTlNihli IU'WfcRTI Circulation Manager\nFr\u00dfct cv \u00dfn HTOmieal 9u o Orin t hnde nt\nMEMBER OF ASSOCIATED PRESS\nKat Arid *t Key W49t. Florida Ad\nS Aco nd Claaa Matter\nCARRIER SUBSCRIPTION RATES\ntUr \u2019\u2019H!\nMonths mi 'tt\n1 Month *\u00ab|J\n144 k MAIL\"RATES\n1 tear tin;\ni Month* J\nI Menn* 4 \u2019J\n(NA Wo4kiy miffaubacriptlona Aeelptlil\nNATIONAL ADVERTISING REPRESENTATIVES:\nTHEIS A SIMPSON. CO.. INC.\n1 84th St, Naw Torn tt. N. T.\nBranch OfHedO In Principal CltlA\u00df\nThe Hot Dog Stand\nThat \"Broke\" A Village\nWith money tight, unemployment down and manu\nfacturing slowed considerably across the nation, Key\nWest and the rest of South Florida are enjoying com\nparatively good times with a few\u2019 exceptions.\nThere has been a business slowdown, it\u2019s true. Turn\ning our backs on it and ignoring it won\u2019t make it go\naway. Neither will loading up on credit or flooding the\nmarket with items for sale. Buf neither and this is\nfor sure will scaring ourselves to death with constant\nworry about it.\nWhat causes a recession, anyway? The cause is\nSimply that people stop buying as much as they\u2019ve been\nbuying. It may be because they\u2019ve already bought all\nthe cars, houses, television sets and hi-fi outfits they\nneed and settle down to enjoy them. It may be that\nthey\u2019re holding back because they can't find what they\nwant at a price they like. Or it may be that something\nscares them into saving all their extra money agaihst\na rainy day, instead of spending a part of the surplus.\nScare talk alone can cause a recession.\nIt\u2019s happened in many a cdtnmunity before.\nAnd among businessmen, there\u2019s an old story the\nparable of the hot dog stand that shows how it hap*\npans better than any wordy theory. We 'can\u2019t remem\nber the tale exactly, but the idea runs something like\nthis:\nA man retired and came South, chose a likely spot\nalong a busy highway and built a hot-dog stand. En\ncouraged because everybody in the neighborhood was\noptimistic about the future, he sank plenty of money\ninto it provided off-street parking, put up flashy neon\nSigns, paid the local printing firm to get up cards for\nmotels nearby and advertised in the local paper. He\nspent money with the local stores for snazzy waitress\nuniforms and the best supplies and the little \u201cextras\u201d\nlike individual mustard-cups and frilly toothpicks to\nhold the \u201cdogs\u201d together.\nThe shining little place attracted lots of attention\nand the man\u2019s business grew by leaps and bounds. It\nkept on growing because he kept on improving it and\nputting up more signs and advertising at more and more\nspots nearby.\nThen one day he got a letter.\nIt came from his son in a northern town.\nAnd the lad told how business there had fallen off\nand how he'd heard it was even worse in other cities\nnearby. He warned, his dad not to expect too good a\nseason. The recession was spreading, he said, and be\nsides, a lot of people wouldn\u2019t be able to go South for\na vacation that winter.\nThe older man got worried, then. He started think\ning about the new roadside signs he\u2019d ordered and won\ndered if he could pay for them. He canceled the order\nand the signmaker got worried. Then he thought\nabout the new stools he'd ordered from the furniture\nhouse, and he canceled that order. The furniture store\nowner started to wonder.\nAnd finally he decided that the upkeep on his bill\nboards was pretty high, so he let that contract lapse,\ntoo, and decided maybe his waitresses could get through\nthe coming season in their old outfits, even though they\nwere a little worn.\nBut with the signs no longer on the highway, people\nbegan passing by the hot dog stand. And the focal folk\nwho went there by habit noticed that the little \u201cextras\u201d\nweren't there anymore it was just like any old diner\nanywhere. And when they didn\u2019t see his ads and cards\nanymore, they asked him why and he told them how\nhe was sure a recession was coming.\nHe\u2019d made money in that little town.\nThey thought of him as a smart man.\nIf he said a recession was coming, they decided,\nthen it surely was coming and they'd better cut back,\ntoo. So the sign firm didn\u2019t get orders for any more\nsigns and it went out of business; the local paper didn\u2019t\nget as many ads and it laid off some people; the print\nshop didn t get as many card orders and it got worried,\ntoo. The furniture dealer didn\u2019t sell much stock to the\nmotels and other restaurants and he cut back.\nThe paint shop didn t sell as much paint and the\nlittle village didn't shine and gleam so brightly, and\nmore cars began passing through it without stopping.\nA lot of the laid-off people went into the city to seek\njobs and this meant fewer shoppers in the village than\never. Before long, there wasn t a business in the town\nincluding the little hot dog stand that couldn't be\nbought for $5OO and the accounts receivable.\nIf we are afiaid of the dark, then, let's not turn off\nthe light that keeps the darkness away. It is necessary\nin business to spend money to make money and an\nounce of confidence has always paid off in the cash reg\nister better than a pound of fear.\nA college biology professor predicts that after the\nlapse of several hundred years men will have hairless\nheads, spindly legs and no toes. With one of the most\npopular screen stars making feminine hearts flutter\ndespite his totally Bald head, and with no scarcity of\nspindly legs, the professor\u2019^ forecast is not too alarming.\nWHY YOU\u2019D THINK HFD BE PROUD TO PROVE IT\n\\tafi I\nkJ\n'b7~T~\nOrderly Routine In Child\u2019s\nLife May Combat Stuttering\nWINTER PARK Being sure\na child keeps his shoes shined and\nhis school desk neat may help\ncure him of stammering.\nBut not this alone, says Ted\nEmery Jr. who as a child stut\ntered so badly he once fell down\nand rolled on a barn floor when\ntrying to ask the hired man for\na hammer.\n\"An orderly routine in a child\u2019s\ndaily life will help develop an or-{\nderly\u00bbmind,\u201d explains Emery who\nhas grown up to lose virtually all\not his impediment and to direct\nthe fionprofit school system for\nstammerers which his mother de\nveloped years ago because she,\ntoo, had been afflicted.\nThe school is now a family af\nfair: Emery Sr., 69; his wife, 65;\nand Theodore Jr., 37.\nThey carry on the work of the\nEmery Institute through corre\nspondence courses and their stu\ndents have ranged from truck\ndrivers to bank presidents; from\nkindergarten age to 65.\nThe basis of their attack is on\nthe thesis that stammering is a\nlack of mental control.\n\u201cSejdom is a nonstammerer con\nscious of the movement of his vo\ncal organs while he is talking;\nand he isn't conscious of how he\nis going to move them before he\nstarts,\" says Emery.\n\u201cThe stammerer on the other\nhand is constantly conscious of his\nvocal organs, the fear, of what\nothers might think of him and\nmany other things because think\ning of how he is speaking instead\nof what he wants to speak about\nhas become a habit with him.\n\u201cDaily exercises of breathing,\nreading aloud, concentrating, wiH\npower, orderliness and desire to\ntalk well all are phrt of helping\ncure the situation. This helps cre\nate a new habit of thinking to re\nplace the old ftabit.\n\u201cBut not until the fifth lesson\ndo we tell a person to think more\nof what he wants to say instead\nof how he is going to say it.\n\"The eighth lesson is on forget\nting. A banker told \u00abus 'forgetting\nis the whole point in the cure. If\nCrossword Puzzle\n27. Provided\n29. Skill\n30. Seat of the\naffections\n21. Biblical\nking\n32. Myself\n33. Hsrbor,\n34. Land\nmeasures\n35. Stsggers\n37. Greatest\n89. Competitor\n40. CompsnioM\n41. Worked\n43. Egyptian\nriver\n44. Write\n47. Observe\n48. Performer\n49. Superlative\nending\nSO. Colored\n91. Ob,truet\u2019>\u2019\nACKOSB\n1. Flying\nexperts\n8. Provided\nwith shoes\n9. Edict\n12. PoiMH\n13. Persian\nfairy\n14. Card ganta\n15. Dry\nIS. Indian,\n18. Writer of\nthe Psalm,\n20. Color,\n21. Of a\nMediter\nranean\nisland\n23. L^us bright\n24. Narrow\nroad\n25. English\nriver\nwe forget completely that we\nmight stammer and think of the\nsubject matter, then we have con\nquered stammering.\u201d\u2019\nThe school now has 612 corre\nspondence course students; 366\nschool children; and 45 for the\nhome study course which is a new,\nless concentrated course but which\ndistills the information the Emerys\nhave gained over 23 years expe\nrience with the school.\nMrs. Emery cured herself in the\nearly 1920 s and was 43 when she\nwrote out as a lesson her ideas on\nself-correction for Ted Jr., then\n15. The correspondence idea was\nborn and has continued since.\nIn Orange County schools in this\nares,.34B children were instructed\nunder the Emery methods and Ted\nsays 207 were cured; 77 improved;\n6 failed to gain.\nHe says elementary school years\nare the best time to start -pre\nventive work but that adults can\ncure themselves with proper guid\nance.\nthe program for school children\nin this category was developed so\nit could be given without their\nbeing aware of\u2018the corrective\ntherapy. This was the system used\nin Orange County schools.\n\u201cA child will probably be well\naware his routine is being changed\nbut be will probably not know it is\nbeing changed to correct his stam\nmering, which is our point,\" Em\nery says.\n\"But once s stammerer under\nstands that his speech barricade\nis mental and that exercises in\nconcentration and coordination will\nhelp, bis problem is practically\nsolved. Serious study Will accom\nplish the rest.\"\nLams With Sham Ham\nPHOENIX, Ariz. A thief\ndashed into a market, grabbed a\nlarge, cloth wrapped ham\" hang\ning from a hook and escaped in a\nwaiting car. Store owner Stanley\nLee said the thief is in for a\nmighty big disappoinmtent. The\nham was a dummy, made of\nplaster, and strictly for display.\nA B L tlsMv^l Lmm O A\nBslutlen ef Yseterday\u2019s Puds\nDOWN\n1. Sunken\nfence\n2. Automobile\n3. Apparent\n4. Sober\n5. Runner, ot\n,hort race,\n9. Pty\nattention\nT. City in\nNebraska\nI. Remote\nS. Bring int\nline\n10. S\nn.\u2019li;\nhuy\n17. bhort\nskirt\nIS, Govern\nment\nagency:\nabbr.\n21. Shellfish\n22. Onions of\na certain\nsort\nI 23. Induced\nI M. Rodent\n28. Clenched\nhand\n30. Nether\nlands\n31. Wearing\naway\n39. Fruit\n34. Reparation\n30. Occurrence\n38. Size of\nshot\n39. Cable\n40. Measure\n42. Plaything\n44. Meadow\nI 45. Work unit\nSea Secrets\nSea Secret* are prepared by\nThe Marina Laboratory of the\nUniversity of Miami, acting as\nofficial fisheries research agen\ncy for the Florida State Board\nof Conservation. Questions are\nwelcomed and should bo ad\ndressed to Sea Secrets care of\nthis newspaper.\nQuestion:\nI intend to engage in shrimp\nfishing upon my return to the\nUnited States this fall, and would\nappreciate all the information\nyou can give me on shrimping\nin the Gulf of Mexico. B. D. Men\nton, Guam.\nAnswer:\nThe Tortugas and Campeche\nbeds provide 85% of the shrimp\nlanded in Florida at the present\ntime. The Gulf shrimp fishery is\nmade up of three species of\nshrimp: the white shrimp, Penaeus\nsetiferus, the brown shrimp, _ P. as\ntecus; and the pink shrimp, P. du\norarum.\nMost white shrimp are caught off\nthe mouth of the Mississippi\nRiver. Brown' shrimp is caught in\nlarge quantities, with Texas pro\nducing most. Pink shrimp supports\nthe Tortugas fishery, and is the\nprincipal variety caught at Cam\npeche. Royal red shrimp. Hymeno\npenaeus robustus, have been dis\ncovered off Tortugas and off the\nFlorida northeast coast in deep\nwater (1140 to 1800 feet). A few\n\u2019boats with special gear have been\nfishing the latter area since early\n1957.\nSince the development of the\nTortugas and Campeche grdunds,\nTampa, Key West, and Ft. Myers\nhave become Florida's most im\nportant shrimp centers. Shrimp\nboats are also based at several\nother Florida cities. Most boats\nbased at Tampa fish^ampeche,\nmaking trips of from 12 to 25 days.\nFt. Myers boats fish Campeche and\nTortugas. Most Key West boats\nfish Tortugas.\nThe Florida State Board of Con\nservation has a pamphlet entitled\n\u201cThe Commercial Shrimp Instustry\nof Florida\" which is available on\nrequest to its Tallahassee offices.\nI QUESTION:\nWe had a severe eeld snap In\nthe Florida Keys recently, and\nmany of our fishes wore killed.\nI noticed that some kinds, for\nexample, snappers and grunts,\nwore common among thy dead\nfishes, while others, for example,\nchannel bass and bonefish, were\nnot found at all. Why are some\nkinds of fishes killed by cold\ncold when others are not form\ned at all? M. R. Prentice, Mara\nthon, Florida.\nANSWER:\nUnlike mammals and birds,\nwhich have Considerable indepen\nden c e of environmental tem\nperature due to maintenance of\nconstant body temperature, fishes\nare \"cold-blooded\" and are us\nually able to survive only in a rel\natively narrow range of tempera\nture.\nBiochemical reactions within the\nbody do not operate over a wide\nrange of temperature, and a fish\ncan live only within those extrem\nes dictated by all of the biochemi\ncal reactions collectively. Fishes\nliving in cold regions are adapted\nto ranges in the lower part of the\ntemperature scale and those liv\ning in tropical areas to the upper\npart.\nIn Florida waters, many north\nern fishes are living near their\nupper extreme of temperature tol\nerance and many tropical species,\nsuch as grunts, may be killed: the\nnorthern forms, such as croakers,\nusually survive easily.\nThe circumtropical bonefish is\nrecorded from pur east cost as\nfar north as Cape Cod and on the\nwest coast from the cool water of\nMonterey, California. However, the\ntolerance of the bonefish to tem\nperature is unusually great' for a\nmarine fish.\nHal Boyle Says\nBy HAL BOYLE\nNEW YORK UT>\u2014Things a col\numnist might never know if he\ndidn\u2019t open his mail:\nThat boxer John L. Sullivan was\na champ at the table as well as\nthe ring. He could consume 15\npounds of meat at a sitting.\nThat, speaking of meat, your\nown lifetime quota Of animal pro\ntein makes quite a herd: 33 hogs,\n10 lambs, eight Steers and four\nchives.\nThat Burl Ives, who collects\nIrish sayings, likes this one: \"A\nman needs a woman to take care\nof him so that she can make him\nstrong enough for her to lean on.\u201d\nThat science has subdued the\n\u201cblaek death.\u201d In 1057 only 814\ncases were recorded of the bubon\nic plague that once scourged the\n\u25a0world.\nThat it takes Ml million years\nfor heat to travel from the core\nof ths sun to its surface.\nThat by 1943 ft is estimated\nthere will be 100,000 Americans\nalive who are aged 100 years or\nolder.\nThat you probably knew a house\nfly has six legs, but did you know\nspider hss eight?\nThat actor Errol Flynn paid\nthis unusual tribute to his wife,\nPatrice Wymore, and survived:\n\"She\u2019s not my type, but I love\nKiwanis Club\nHears Quintet\nOf Musicians\nA quintet of young muaicans, all\nstudents at Convent of Mary Imma\nculate, entertained members of\nKey West Kiwanis Club at the\ngroup's weekly dinnar-maating at\nLogun\u2019s Restaurant Tuesday.\nMichael Lanasa, who plays alto\nsax; Jerry Torano, drums; Rett\nThompson, trumpet; Vivian Garing,\npiano; and Mario Martines, who\ndirects the group, were praaanfed\nby Dr. Allen Shepard.\nThe 15-minute program included\na Cuban number, \"Ricacha\" and\nsuch hits as \u201cHe,\u201d \"Ballin' the\nJack,\u201d \"Rock Around the Clock,\"\n\u201cAround the World\" and the old\nfavorite \"Little Brown Jug.\u201d\nPresident Bill Warner reminded\nthe club that next Tuesday\u2019s meet\ning, April 22, marks the organiza\ntion's 10th anniversary. A \u201cLadies\nNight\" program is planned.\nSkippy Rueda, acting as secre\ntary in Ira Albury\u2019s absence, gave\na brief report and Manuel Lopez\npresented guests, who included\nBenny Trevor and Jack Holcomb\nfrom the Kiwanis-sponsored Key\nWest High School Key Club\nand Ted Roehrs, visiting Kiwanian\nfrom Bloomington, New Jersey.\nMembers sang a \u201chappy birthday\"\nto past president Joe Boza.\nBreak Reported\nIn Unemployment\nDENVER (B Jame, Noonan,\ndeputy director of the State De\npartment of Employment, reports\nthe first msjor break in unem\nployment in Colorado.\nHe estimated that 35,000 Colo\nradoans still are seeking jobs, but\nadded that the figure represents\na decrease of nearly 3,700 in a\nsingle week.\n\u201cThe first downward trend of\nany sizable amount since last\nSeptember was reflected in the\nweek ending last Thursday,\u201d he\nsaid, when $403,315 was paid to\n14,463 claimants. During the pre\nvious wee kending April 3, he said,\nclaims totaled 15,311.\nKey West\nIn Days Gone By\nApril U. 1m\nHome construction in Key West\nis increasing, City Building Ins\npector Harry Baker reported to\nday. He said that more than $15,-\n000 in building permits had been\nissued last week.\nCelebrations marking the twen\nty fifth anniversary of the first\nairplane flight between Key West\nand Cuba will be held here and in\nCuba during May.\nApril U, IMB\nSix Cuban firemen from Ha\nvana arrived here today. For the\nnext week they will be guests of\nmembers of the Key West Fire\nDepartment. A dinner and a dance\nare on the schedule of events.\nSeven slot machines were seis\ned in raids by city police on three\nbars last night. Police Lieut. Har\nry Lee Baker said the raids were\npart of the city\u2019s plan to stamp\nout illegal gambling.\nCamel Power Help*\nLONDON te-Rcd China Radio\nsays camel power is speeding up\nspring sowing in Kansu Province.\nA Peiping broadcast adds that\npeasants were surprised to find\nhf'oig Asian camels pulled double\nblade wheeled plows twice as fast\nas oxen can.\nher.\" Could you say that at home,\nand get away with It?\nThat all U.S. mailmen don't de\nliver on foot. There are 435 horse\nback routes, 10 boat routes, and\n32 employing airplanes.\nThat the nation\u2019s first subway\nwasn't built in New York. Boston\nIvon the honor in 1007.\nThat ths most sociable of all\nmammals is the prairie dog. And\nall this time we thought it was\nthat gay old dog down the block 1\nfrom us.\nThat if you check A. OOnan\nDoyle's books you will find he nev\ner once had Sherlock Holmes say,\n\u201cElementary, my dear Watson.\"\nThat\u2014here\u2019s a sidelight on mod\nern morality\u2014a 42nd St. novelty\nstore here has displays of religi\nous objects and switph blade\nknives side by side in the window.\nThat perhaps the world\u2019s most\nprevalent childhood disease is a\nform of protein malnutrition. It\nis estimated half to two-thirds of\nall children suffer from it. s\nThat no physician has ever been\nelected president of the United\nStates. But William Henry Harri\nson, the 9th president, did study\nmedicine in his youth.\nThat if you are 40 years old now\nthe ehsnees are 13 out of II that\nyou will live to be 65. But only\none in 13 that you'll be financially\nindependent.\nThat the Chinese believe playing\ncards were invented in the year\n1120 by their emperor, Leun-ho, as\na diversion for his wives. A Hindu\nlegend holds they were invented\nby a maharajah's wife to cure\nher husband of pulling his beard,\nThat it was Benjamin Franklin\nwho observed, \u201cThe way to be\nsafe is never to be secure.\"\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nRadio and Television Listings\nc?\nCHANNEL 4 TV WTVJ\nnVBSDAI BVENINS\nf;U Swrt* Show*r Stir*\nS:M WriUw 30 mayhouw W*\nS:M Raalek ilm N*wt\nNawa- 11:10 Weat